Intro to Machine Learning Workshop

Goal: In this workshop, you will train machine learning models to identify regions of the genome that change their chromatin accessibility between ovarian cancer cells that are sensitive vs. resistant to platinum-based chemotherapeutics like cisplatin. You will use features of these genomic regions like their chromatin accessibility and presence of platinum adducts in other relevant cell types.

Background: The data for this project come from the recent paper: https://clinicalepigeneticsjournal.biomedcentral.com/articles/10.1186/s13148-021-01105-6 Please see it and the lecture slides for background on this project. The raw data generated in this paper are available from GEO: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/geo/query/acc.cgi?acc=GSE149147

Materials: You have been provided a tab-delimited text file (gallon21_peo1_v_peo4_access_data.tab) that contains the coordinates of genomic regions (in reference to the hg19/GRCh37 genome build) that either change (positives) or do not change (negatives) their chromatin accessibility between cisplatin sensitive ovarian cancer cells (PEO1) and cisplatin-resistant ovarian cancer cells (PEO4). This file also contains many attributes of these genomic regions that you will use as features in the machine learning models you train.

The columns are: chrom: the chromosome of the region (hg19)

start: the starting chromosome coordinate (hg19) of the region

stop: the ending chromosome coordinate (hg19) of the region

a2780_access: the average chromatin accessibility of this region in a2780 cells (see manuscript for description of cell types)

cp70_access: the average chromatin accessibility of this region in cp70 cells

PEA1_access: the average chromatin accessibility of this region in PEA1 cells

PEA2_access: the average chromatin accessibility of this region in PEA2 cells

PEO1_access: the average chromatin accessibility of this region in PEO1 cells

PEO1_pt: the average pt-Exo-seq signal for PEO1 cells

PEO4_pt: the average pt-Exo-seq signal for PEO4 cells promoter_overlap: whether the region overlaps a gene’s promoter region

And finally, we have the label we want to predict: diff_access_PEO1_v_PEO4: whether the region was differentially accessible between PEO1 and PEO4 cells on average.

Step 3: Creating a training data set

Set aside 20% of the positives and negatives as a test set for use in Step 3. The remaining 80% will be your training/validation set for us in this step.

set.seed(14) # Set a random seed so that same sample can be reproduced in future runs


sample <- sample.int(n = nrow(data), size = floor(.8*nrow(data)), replace = F)
train <- data[sample, ]  # Select the rows corresponding to the sample
test  <- data[-sample, ] # Select all rows except the ones in the sample

#scaling the train and test dataset separately
train <- train %>%
  mutate(across(c(a2780_access, cp70_access, PEA1_access, PEA2_access, PEO1_access, PEO1_pt, PEO4_pt), ~scale(.)[, 1]))

test <- test %>%
  mutate(across(c(a2780_access, cp70_access, PEA1_access, PEA2_access, PEO1_access, PEO1_pt, PEO4_pt), ~scale(.)[, 1]))

1. Did you select regions for the test set randomly or by another criteria? Why?

I randomly selected regions for the test set to ensure an unbiased and representative distribution of the data. Random selection helps prevent any unintended patterns or biases that might arise if the test set were chosen based on specific criteria. This approach ensures that the model is evaluated on a diverse and unseen subset of data, making the results more generalizable to new data. Additionally, random sampling helps maintain the class distribution (ratio of positives to negatives) in both training and test sets, preventing imbalanced learning.

Step 4: Training Machine Learning Models

Train at least two supervised ML models on the data.

I have included packages for two commonly used ones, Random Forest and XGBoost You can find more information on ways to use them here

Random Forest: https://www.r-bloggers.com/2021/04/random-forest-in-r/

XGBoost: https://xgboost.readthedocs.io/en/stable/R-package/xgboostPresentation.html

  1. Which models did you select and why?

I selected two models: Random Forest and XGBoost.

Random Forest: This model is robust to overfitting, handles high-dimensional data well, and can measure feature importance, making it great for biological datasets with potentially complex interactions between variables.

XGBoost: This model is highly efficient and often outperforms other models on structured data due to its ability to handle non-linear relationships and optimize performance through boosting. It’s also well-suited for handling imbalanced datasets, which can be common in biological data like this.

These two models complement each other, allowing us to compare a tree-based ensemble method with a boosting approach to see which better captures the patterns in chromatin accessibility related to cisplatin resistance.

Train the Models

rf <- randomForest(
  x = rf_train %>% select(-diff_access_PEO1_v_PE04),
  y = as.factor(rf_train$diff_access_PEO1_v_PE04),
  ntree = 500,
  mtry = sqrt(ncol(rf_train)-1),
  importance = TRUE)


train_x <- train_x %>%
  mutate(across(where(is.character), as.numeric))

test_x <- test_x %>%
  mutate(across(where(is.character), as.numeric))

dtrain <- xgb.DMatrix(data = as.matrix(train_x), label = train_y)
dtest <- xgb.DMatrix(data = as.matrix(test_x), label = test_y)

xgb <- xgboost(data = dtrain,
               nrounds = 100,
               max_depth = 6,
               eta = 0.3, 
               objective = "binary:logistic",
               verbose = 0)
  1. Do any of the models have hyperparameters? If so, how did you decide how to set them?

Yes, both models have hyperparameters:

Random Forest:

ntree = 500: The number of trees was set to 500 to ensure a stable model without overfitting. Increasing trees usually improves performance but comes at a computational cost.

mtry = sqrt(ncol(rf_train) - 1): This is a common heuristic for classification problems, selecting the square root of the number of features for each split to reduce correlation between trees and improve generalization.

importance = TRUE: This allows extraction of feature importance to interpret which genomic features contribute most to the model’s decisions.

XGBoost:

nrounds = 100: The number of boosting rounds was set to 100 to balance training time and performance.

max_depth = 6: A max depth of 6 allows the model to capture some complexity in the data while preventing overfitting.

eta = 0.3: This is the learning rate, controlling the step size at each boosting iteration. A value of 0.3 is a reasonable default for quick convergence.

objective = “binary:logistic”: Since we’re dealing with a binary classification problem, this objective function is appropriate for predicting probabilities of belonging to the positive class.

The hyperparameters were chosen as reasonable defaults, but they could be fine-tuned through cross-validation to further optimize performance.

Apply the models to data from the training set

pred_rf <- predict(rf, rf_train %>% select(-diff_access_PEO1_v_PE04))
pred_xgb <- predict(xgb, as.matrix(train_x))
  1. Do the models’ predictions agree and do they predict the correct label?

To assess agreement, we can compare the predictions from both models on the training set. If they align closely, it indicates that both models are capturing similar patterns in the data. However, if they diverge, it could imply that each model is picking up on different features or relationships. To check correctness, we can look at the ROC curve. This will show how well each model predicts the labels. If both models perform similarly, it may suggest that the patterns in the data are strong and consistent.

  1. Why should we view this prediction as biased?

These predictions are made on the training set, where the models have already seen the data. Evaluating performance on the same data used for training often leads to overfitting, where the model memorizes patterns instead of generalizing them. As a result, the performance metrics on the training set may be overly optimistic and not representative of how the model will perform on unseen data. That’s why we set aside a test set earlier — to get an unbiased estimate of performance. Cross-validation can also help reduce bias by ensuring the model is evaluated on different subsets of data during training.

  1. How many folds of cross validation did you use? Why?

I used 10-fold cross-validation. This means the training data was split into 10 subsets, and the model was trained on 9 subsets while the 10th was used for validation. This process repeated 10 times, with each subset serving as the validation set once. Ten-fold CV is a common choice because it strikes a good balance between computational efficiency and performance estimation stability. It reduces bias (as every data point gets a chance to be in the validation set) and variance (by averaging performance across multiple folds), giving a more reliable estimate of the model’s performance.

  1. What evaluation metrics did you use (e.g., accuracy, confusion matrix, ROC curve, PR curve)? Why?

I used the ROC (Receiver Operating Characteristic) AUC (Area Under the Curve) as the evaluation metric. ROC AUC measures the model’s ability to distinguish between classes and is especially useful in imbalanced datasets, as it evaluates performance across all classification thresholds. A higher AUC indicates a better-performing model, with 1.0 representing perfect discrimination and 0.5 indicating no better performance than random guessing. It’s widely used because it gives a more holistic view of model performance beyond just accuracy, especially in datasets where false positives and false negatives may have different consequences.

rf_roc <- roc(test_y, rf_probs, levels = c(0, 1), direction = "<")
xgb_roc <- roc(test_y, xgb_probs, levels = c(0, 1), direction = "<")

# Interpolate both ROC curves to have the same number of points
n_points <- 100  # Number of points to interpolate

# Interpolation for Random Forest
rf_fpr_interp <- seq(0, 1, length.out = n_points)
rf_sens_interp <- approx(rf_roc$specificities, rf_roc$sensitivities, xout = 1 - rf_fpr_interp)$y

  1. How did it perform compared to on the training set?

The XGBoost model performed better on the training set (accuracy: 0.804, ROC: 0.8624) compared to the test set (accuracy: 0.739, ROC: 0.7697). This gap suggests that the model may be slightly overfitting to the training data, capturing nuances that don’t generalize as well to unseen data.

  1. Does the model consistently make one kind of error (e.g. calling positive instances negatives or negative instances positives)?

Errors in the Training Set: - False Negatives (FN) = 105: The model is incorrectly classifying positive instances (class 1) as negative (class 0). This means that positive instances are being missed, leading to a low sensitivity of 0.5307.

  • False Positives (FP) = 245: The model is incorrectly classifying negative instances (class 0) as positive (class 1). This is also affecting the model’s precision (positive predictive value), which is 0.7251.

Errors in the Test Set: - False Negatives (FN) = 23: The model is incorrectly classifying positive instances (class 1) as negative (class 0). This results in a lower sensitivity of 0.4366 in the test set.

  • False Positives (FP) = 80: The model is incorrectly classifying negative instances (class 0) as positive (class 1). This affects the positive predictive value (precision), which is 0.7294 on the test set.

Analysis of the Errors: False Negatives (FN) are consistent in both the training and test sets. This suggests the model has a bias towards predicting negative instances (class 0), and it tends to miss positive cases (class 1), leading to a lower sensitivity. False Positives (FP) are also present in both the training and test sets, but specificity remains high, especially on the test set. This suggests that the model is better at identifying negatives than positives.

Does the model consistently make one kind of error? Yes, the model consistently makes errors by classifying positive instances as negative (False Negatives). This is especially evident from the low sensitivity in both the training and test sets, which reflects the model’s difficulty in detecting positive instances.

  1. Is this performance “good”? How would you decide if it needs to be better?

In biological research or clinical settings, a higher ROC (>0.8) is usually preferred, especially if the consequences of false negatives or false positives are significant. Since the test ROC is ~0.77, the model is performing decently but might benefit from further tuning, feature engineering, or trying alternative algorithms.
